	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Discussions on regional food and nutrition security policy continue</h1>

			
			<h4>
												30 August 2010
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>In July 2010 discussions took place at a CARIFORUM workshop on a draft Regional Policy for Food and Nutrition Security. Key objectives of the policy are identified as:</p>
<ul>

<li>raising the living standards of the population, particularly the most vulnerable;</li>

<li>promoting sustainable production, commercialisation, and consumption of affordable, quality Caribbean food commodities;</li>

<li>enhancing the role of regional markets and trade;</li>

<li>improving the food and nutritional security of the region.</li>

</ul>
<p>The creation of risk management mechanisms, including Caribbean-wide agriculture/crop insurance schemes and establishing ‘adequate protection against climate- and pest-related threats’, were identified as priorities.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>According to press reports, the draft policy envisages ‘a greater say by producers in the agricultural sector, including farmers, fishermen and agro-processors in a regional agriculture research agenda that employs a market-driven and value-chain approach.’ Adequate incentives based on pricing, marketing, and food distribution and input-supply policies are seen as necessary to encourage investment in agriculture and agri-processing activities. ‘The creation of a predictable fiscal, trade and regulatory policy environment for agricultural, livestock and other food production in the region and the creation of vertical and horizontal linkages between tourism, agro-food distribution services, agro-food manufacturing and the productive sector’ is also seen as necessary in the policy. </p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>A ‘regional agricultural trade and import policy aimed at keeping dependence on imported foods “at the absolute minimum’ is seen as increasingly important, given the increased global price instability within a trend towards rising prices. Improving the regional food distribution system by removing non-tariff barriers to intra-regional trade is also seen as important.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>&nbsp;</p><p><i>Stabroek News</i>, ‘CARICOM food security workshop to ponder how to boost agri investment’,<i> </i>23 July 2010</p><p>
<a href="http://www.stabroeknews.com/2010/business/07/23/caricom-food-security-workshop-to-ponder-how-to-boost-agri-investment/" target="_self">http://www.stabroeknews.com/2010/business/07/23/caricom-food-security-wo...</a></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>CARICOM/FAO/Cooperazione Italiana, ‘Proceedings of the first regional workshop for the formulation of a regional policy for food and nutrition security in the Caribbean’, 30 Nov - 1 December 2009</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>
<a href="http://www.rlc.fao.org/progesp/pesa/caricom2/pdf/pubs05.pdf" target="_self">http://www.rlc.fao.org/progesp/pesa/caricom2/pdf/pubs05.pdf</a></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>CARICOM, point of access for downloading OTN/CRNM briefs dealing with trade in goods under the CARIFORUM-EC EPA</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>
<a href="http://www.crnm.org/index.php?option=com_docman&amp;task=cat_view&amp;gid=124&amp;Itemid=95" target="_self">http://www.crnm.org/index.php?option=com_docman&amp;task=cat_view&amp;gi...</a></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><i>Dominican Today</i>, ‘Official says Dominican Republic and Haiti don’t need free trade pact’,<i> </i>6 July 2010</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>
<a href="http://www.dominicantoday.com/dr/economy/2010/7/6/36235/Official-says-Dominican-Republic-Haiti-dont-need-free-trade-pact" target="_self">http://www.dominicantoday.com/dr/economy/2010/7/6/36235/Official-says-Do...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>A complex relationship may develop between the CARIFORUM-EU EPA and this emerging policy emphasis on a regional agricultural trade and import policy that reduces dependence on imported foods to ‘the absolute minimum’. On the one hand, the EPA contains a special chapter on agriculture (Chapter 5, Title 1, Part II) which is intended to encourage the sustainable development of the CARIFORUM agricultural sector. According to the Caribbean Regional Negotiating Machinery (now known as the Office of Trade Negotiations – OTN), these provisions were specifically designed to contribute to food security, poverty eradication and diversification, through the enhancement of competitiveness and innovation, and to provide a framework for positive support to the agriculture sector. On the other hand, the EPA requires the CARIFORUM states generally to liberalise imports. However, as the CRNM has noted, most countries have excluded key agricultural products from their liberalisation commitments. Indeed, tariff protection has been retained on products accounting for 74% of the value of food and agricultural imports from the EU over the 2002-2004 period. Moreover, EPA safeguard provisions have been tailored to the needs of CARIFORUM food and agricultural producers, including through securing EU commitments to the elimination of export subsidies on all agricultural products on which CARIFORUM has agreed to eliminate tariffs. This means that few, if any, tariffs on items that are important in terms of food security to the Caribbean, and that are produced by the EU, will be removed in the short to medium term. The limited tariff elimination commitments on agricultural products that are made by CARIFORUM governments will be largely ‘back-loaded’ (i.e., they will only take place at the end of an extensive tariff phase-down period).</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The most significant changes impacting on the food and agriculture sector in the Caribbean are likely to be brought about by requirements under the EPA (particularly Articles 26 and 27) to eliminate discriminatory restrictions such as import licensing and other charges on imports that are maintained by some CARIFORUM states. This could result in the expansion of EU exports in the affected product areas.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The EPA could also result in increased regional<i> </i>imports. Countries must liberalise towards each other (including the Dominican Republic) as well as towards the EU, and some of the non-tariff barriers to regional imports currently applied by some CARIFORUM states may be illegal under the EPA provisions. This may in part account for the assertion by officials from the Dominican Republic that the Dominican Republic and Haiti have no need to sign a free-trade agreement to spur cross-border commerce, and that instead they must simply adhere to the provisions of the CARIFORUM-EU EPA.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
